## 6. Streamlabs

### Primary Sources
- **Developer Docs:** https://dev.streamlabs.com
- **REST API:** https://dev.streamlabs.com/reference
- **Socket API (real-time events):** https://dev.streamlabs.com/docs/socket-api
- **OAuth 2.0:** https://dev.streamlabs.com/docs/oauth

### What It Is
Two separate APIs: REST (management) and Socket.IO (real-time events). The Socket API is the valuable one for OIS — it fires events the moment someone follows, subscribes, donates, or cheers.

**Note:** Streamlabs ≠ Streamlabs OBS. The API works regardless of which streaming software you use (OBS with Streamlabs plugin, or Streamlabs Desktop).

---

### Authentication
OAuth 2.0. Register app at dev.streamlabs.com. User grants access, you get access token.

**⚠️ Token expiry:** Access tokens expire after ~60 minutes. Refresh tokens do not expire. Build your integration to handle token refresh — don't assume an access token stays valid across sessions or stream restarts. Source: https://streamlabs.readme.io/reference/oauth-2

**Scopes:**
| Scope | What It Allows |
|---|---|
| `alerts.create` | Trigger custom alerts |
| `donations.read` | Read donation history |
| `donations.create` | Create a donation (testing) |
| `socket.token` | Access real-time Socket API |
| `points.read` | Read loyalty points |
| `credits.write` | Add to stream credits |

---

### REST API Key Endpoints

| Endpoint | Method | What It Does |
|---|---|---|
| `GET /donations` | GET | List donation history |
| `POST /api/v2.0/alerts` | POST | Trigger a custom alert overlay (v2 endpoint — use this, not `/alerts`) |
| `GET /points` | GET | Get user loyalty points |
| `POST /credits/roll` | POST | Trigger credits roll |
| `GET /socket/token` | GET | Get token for Socket connection |

**Alert rate limit:** Streamlabs recommends no more than 2 alerts per minute per user. Source: https://dev.streamlabs.com/reference/alerts

---

### Socket API (Real-Time Events)

This is the reason to use Streamlabs for OIS automation. It fires events in real time as they happen on stream.

**Connect:**
```javascript
const io = require('socket.io-client');
const token = 'your_socket_token'; // from REST API
const socket = io(`https://sockets.streamlabs.com?token=${token}`, {
  transports: ['websocket']
});

socket.on('event', (data) => {
  const events = JSON.parse(data);
  events.forEach(event => handleEvent(event));
});
```

**Event Types:**

| `type` | `for` | What It Means |
|---|---|---|
| `follow` | YouTube/Twitch/Facebook | New follower |
| `subscription` | YouTube/Twitch | New subscriber/member |
| `resub` | Twitch | Resubscription with streak |
| `donation` | Streamlabs | Donation received |
| `bits` | Twitch | Bits cheered |
| `superchat` | YouTube | SuperChat received |
| `host` | Twitch | Channel hosted |
| `raid` | Twitch | Raid received |
| `merch` | Streamlabs Merch | Merch purchase (Streamlabs only) |

**Event Payload Example (subscription):**
```json
{
  "type": "subscription",
  "for": "youtube_account",
  "message": [{
    "name": "Jake Hirsch",
    "months": 1,
    "message": "First month. Let's go.",
    "amount": "1",
    "gifted": false
  }]
}
```

**Rate Limit:** Streamlabs recommends no more than 2 alert triggers per minute to avoid alert queue backup.

---

### OIS Use Cases

**Real-Time OBS Scene Switching:**
```
Socket event: new YouTube subscriber
→ OBS WebSocket: switch to Scrivener welcome scene
→ Play typewriter animation (Holdt's hands)
→ Display: "[Name] has wet their quill. Welcome, Scrivener."
→ After 8 seconds: return to writing scene
```

**Custom Alert Triggers:**
```
Socket event: SuperChat received
→ Log to Notion: supporter name, amount, message
→ Trigger Streamlabs custom alert: display message on stream
```

**Raid Response:**
```
Socket event: raid
→ OBS: switch to Outside Inn warmup scene briefly (welcome the raid)
→ Discord: post in #announcements that a raid came in
```

**Note on Streamlabs vs. OBS alerts directly:**
OBS has its own browser source alerts (via obs-browser alert plugins or custom HTML). Streamlabs adds a managed alert layer on top. For OIS, the custom HTML overlay approach (already proven on Broadcast Alpha) may be cleaner than adding Streamlabs dependency — but Streamlabs is significantly easier for non-engineers. Evaluate both.

---

## 7. Notion

### Primary Sources
- **API Reference:** https://developers.notion.com/reference
- **Getting Started:** https://developers.notion.com/docs/getting-started
- **Webhooks (2025):** https://developers.notion.com/docs/webhooks
- **MCP Server:** https://github.com/makenotion/notion-mcp-server
- **Database Query Guide:** https://developers.notion.com/reference/post-database-query
- **Block Types:** https://developers.notion.com/reference/block

### What It Is
Notion's API is a REST API that treats everything as pages, blocks, and databases. You can read and write almost everything in Notion programmatically. The MCP server integration with Claude is already live in this project.

---

### Authentication
Create an "Integration" in Notion developer settings → get an API token → share specific pages/databases with the integration.

**Token:** `Bearer ntn_XXXX...` in Authorization header.

**Required version header:** Every request must include `Notion-Version: 2025-09-03` (current as of March 2026). Omitting this header causes errors. Source: https://developers.notion.com/reference/versioning

**Important:** The integration only sees pages/databases that have been explicitly shared with it. It can't access your whole workspace by default — you must share each database you want it to touch.

---

### Rate Limits
- ~3 requests/second average (burst allowed)
- 429 responses if exceeded — use exponential backoff
- Batch operations where possible

---

### Key Endpoints

**Databases:**
```
GET  /v1/databases/{id}                  — Get database schema
POST /v1/databases/{id}/query            — Query rows (with filters)
POST /v1/databases                       — Create new database
PATCH /v1/databases/{id}                 — Update database schema
```

**Pages (Rows):**
```
POST /v1/pages                           — Create new row/page
PATCH /v1/pages/{id}                     — Update row properties
GET  /v1/pages/{id}                      — Get page/row data
DELETE /v1/pages/{id}                    — Archive (soft delete)
```

**Markdown API (official, as of 2025-09-03 version):**
```
GET   /v1/pages/{page_id}/markdown       — Retrieve page content as Markdown
POST  /v1/pages/markdown                 — Create page from Markdown
PATCH /v1/pages/{id}/markdown            — Update page content via Markdown
```
Source: https://developers.notion.com/reference/retrieve-page-markdown + https://developers.notion.com/guides/data-apis/working-with-markdown-content

**OIS use case:** Pipe ONCE myth drafts (written in Notion) directly to Claude API as Markdown for consistency checks — no manual copy-paste. Also useful for exporting Brand Bible sections programmatically.

**Multi-Source Databases (version 2025-09-03+):**
Notion now supports databases that pull from multiple sources. If you're using these, API responses include a `data_source_id` field. Automations that write to or query these databases must handle `data_source_id` — omitting it can cause silent failures. Source: https://developers.notion.com/docs/upgrade-guide-2025-09-03

**File Uploads:**
Small files (guides for ≤20MB): use the standard upload endpoint. Larger files require multipart upload — different flow. Do not assume a single size limit; check the multipart spec before building. Source: https://developers.notion.com/guides/data-apis/uploading-small-files

**Blocks (Content):**
```
GET  /v1/blocks/{id}/children            — Get page content blocks
PATCH /v1/blocks/{id}                    — Update a block
POST /v1/blocks/{id}/children            — Append blocks to page
DELETE /v1/blocks/{id}                   — Delete a block
```

**Search:**
```
POST /v1/search                          — Search across workspace (what's shared with integration)
```

---

### Database Query with Filters

```json
POST /v1/databases/{id}/query
{
  "filter": {
    "property": "Status",
    "select": { "equals": "Active" }
  },
  "sorts": [
    { "property": "Joined", "direction": "descending" }
  ]
}
```

Supports complex AND/OR filter combinations, all Notion property types.

---

### Webhooks (2025)

Notion added native webhooks. Fires when pages are created, updated, or deleted in databases you've connected.

**Setup:** Dashboard → Settings → Connections → Automations (or via API).

**Events:**
- `page.created` — new row added
- `page.properties_updated` — row edited
- `page.content_updated` — page body changed
- `page.deleted` — page archived

**OIS Use Cases:**
- Watch ONCE writing goals database: when a milestone is marked Complete → trigger Discord announcement
- Watch Members database: when a new Keeper is manually added → trigger welcome flow

---

### OIS Databases to Build

**Members CRM:**
| Property | Type | Source |
|---|---|---|
| Name | Title | Fourthwall webhook |
| Email | Email | Fourthwall webhook |
| Tier | Select (Scrivener/Keeper) | Fourthwall webhook |
| Joined | Date | Fourthwall webhook |
| Discord Handle | Text | Manual / Discord bot |
| Notes | Text | Manual |
| Founding # | Number | Manual |
| Active | Checkbox | Fourthwall cancellation webhook |

**Stream Sessions:**
| Property | Type | Source |
|---|---|---|
| Date | Date | OBS StreamStateChanged event |
| Duration | Number (minutes) | OBS calculation |
| Writing Goal | Text | Manual pre-stream |
| ONCE Progress | Select | Manual |
| Peak Viewers | Number | YouTube Analytics |
| New Scriveners | Number | Fourthwall webhook count |
| New Keepers | Number | Fourthwall webhook count |
| Notes | Text | Manual post-stream |

**ONCE Writing Goals:**
Already exists presumably — sync completions back via API as they're updated.

